________________________________

Sent: Monday, November 6, 2023 9:48 AM
Subject: [Register] ARISE (Venture Building) Demo Day on 17 Nov 2023




[cid:image001.png@01D9FC34.611CDA00]



ARISE is a research commercialization programme that supports researchers to move beyond customer validation to venture creation. Through the programme, research teams learn to develop their business models, business strategies, operations, financial projections and pitching skills with the objective to translate their technology to market.



4 ARISE teams will showcase their technology and commericalise innovation outcomes after eight weeks of hard work.  The teams presenting will include:





[cid:image002.jpg@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

PARIS

An innovative tethered aerial robotics system for solar panel cleaning that employs a proprietary aerial robotics technology with a rub-and-rinse mechanism to ensure safe, efficient, and sustainable cleaning of solar panels to maximize energy output. Prof Foong Shaohui leads the team.



[cid:image003.png@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

Magic3D

An advanced Multi-material 3D printer system that supports a wide range of liquid materials, from soft elastomers to silicone-compatible hard epoxies, enables automated integration of continuous fibres. Unlocking possibilities and widening the scope of 3D printing capabilities. Prof Pablo Valdivia leads the team.







[cid:image004.jpg@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

NeatSens

Specially designed yarns equipped with electronically enabled knitwear that would enable uninterrupted and accurate monitoring of joint load and mobility. The tech enables remote monitoring of patients’ physiotherapy sessions in the comfort of their homes and provides crucial actionable insights for effective physical training outcomes and performance analysis. Prof Low Hong Yee leads the team.





[cid:image005.jpg@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

IM2Cell

Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) is widespread around the world and poses a serious threat to public health. Present Antimicrobial Susceptibility Testing (AST) at hospitals and medical facilities is slow (14-20 hours). IM2Cell’s label-free microfluidic bacterial analysis platform currently can provide quantitative AST results within 30 minutes. Prof Ye Ai leads the team.

Preview:: From: SUTD Housing <ecchousing@sutd.edu.sg> Sent: Monday, November 6, 2023 12:47 PM To: Student - Lim Qin Xin <qinxin_lim@mymail.sutd.edu.sg> Subject: Refresher of Hostel's DOs &

________________________________
From: SUTD Housing <ecchousing@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Monday, November 6, 2023 12:47 PM
To: Student - Lim Qin Xin <qinxin_lim@mymail.sutd.edu.sg>
Subject: Refresher of Hostel's DOs & Donts


Dear Residents,



We hope that you have had a restful recess week and are all ready to tackle the upcoming school weeks.

Here’s a refresher of the Do’s & Dont’s whilst staying in the hostel.

Do take note of Pt 4 concerning the restrictions on the usage of Active Mobility Devices.

  1.  Security

  *   Register all your visitors using the Visitors Registration Form before bringing them up to your room
  *   Always accompany visitors. Do not let them wander around or leave them on their own(even if they know where the toilet is, accompany and wait for them outside)
  *   Stayover is strictly disallowed
  *   Ensure that your visitors leave the hostel by 11pm (Visiting hours: 8am till 11pm)
  *   Residents who notice any suspicious person in the hostel are to inform Security or the House Guardians immediately
  *   Never tamper with secured access points (eg. common toilet doors, lift lobby doors, fire-exit doors and gates)
  *   Always lock your room doors for your own safety



  1.  No Smoking/Vaping on Campus

  *   The campus is a smoke-free and vape-free zone
  *   Vaping is a criminal offence under the law and anyone found vaping or possessing a vaporiser will be reported to the authorities
  *   Smoking is only permitted at designated smoking points on campus or outside the University’s perimeters



  1.  No Alcohol Consumption on Campus

  *   This includes the entire hostel premise
  *   Drinking is only allowed at a licensed F&B outlet (D’ Star Bistro)



  1.  Restrictions on Usage of Active Mobility Devices

  *   This includes:

  *   Bicycles and power-assisted bikes
  *   Motorized and non-motorized Personal Mobility Devices (PMDs)

(eg. kick-scooters, skateboards, rollerblades, electric scooters, hoverboards, unicycles, etc.)

  *   Hostel premises: Hand-carry or push only (no riding along corridors or on the ground floor)
  *   Main campus: Dismount and hand-carry/push in restricted areas (eg. Campus Centre)



  1.  Quiet Hours (11pm to 8am)

  *   Keep noise level LOW during Quiet Hours as fellow residents may be studying, resting or sleeping
  *   Noise issues can be directly reported to Security or the House Guardians



  1.  Hostel Corridors

  *   In accordance with fire safety regulations, keep the corridors free of bulky items, fire and trip hazards

(shoes, pails, scooters should not stick out at odd angles or block the passage way)



7.    Common Spaces

  *   Common spaces (eg. corridors, air-con ledges, meeting and study rooms etc) are to be kept clutter-free at all times
  *   Personal items like scooters, bicycles, bags and project materials should not be left in common spaces
  *   Any obstruction or unattended items in the common spaces along the corridors will be immediately removed by Security



8.     Assignment of Beds

  *   Residents are reminded not to change rooms and/or beds without prior approval from Office of Housing
  *   Subletting, in whole or in part, is strictly disallowed

·

9.      Shoe Racks

  *   Any personal shoe racks found lying at the corridors will be removed and disposed without further notice. This includes shoes boxes and any items that are considered combustible.



 Do feel free to contact us should you require any further clarification or assistance!



Regards
Office of Housing

Subject:: Fw: 2023 Registration for Urban Sketching
Preview:: From: ASD <asd@sutd.edu.sg> Sent: Monday, November 6, 2023 10:31 AM Subject: 2023 Registration for Urban Sketching Dear Students We are now accepting registration for Urban Sketching course!
Message Body::
________________________________
From: ASD <asd@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Monday, November 6, 2023 10:31 AM
Subject: 2023 Registration for Urban Sketching




Dear Students



We are now accepting registration for Urban Sketching course!





[cid:image001.png@01D9FAC1.A2C0D980]





Urban Sketching is a 10-session workshop organised by the Architecture and Sustainable Design (ASD) Pillar from 22 January to 27 April 2023. The workshop is designed to equip participants with fundamental sketching skills, with a focus on urban fabrics and landscapes.



For ASD students, do note that this workshop is a graduation requirement. For non-ASD students, this workshop is recommended if you want to pick up a new skill and stretch your creativity.



The lesson details are as follows:



Lessons will be held for 10 weeks during term time, on every Friday, from 2 – 5pm. With the completion of the workshop, participants get to showcase their work through an exhibition in school.



Lesson structure

  *   Sessions 1 to 4                     In SUTD Campus
  *   Sessions 5 to 9                     Outdoor Sketching
  *   Session 10                             Exhibition



Topics covered

  *   Drawing & Tonal Values
  *   Drawing with View Finder
  *   Perspective Drawing
  *   Outdoor Sketching & Perspective
  *   Outdoor Sketching & Rendering
  *   Outdoor Sketching and Principles of Visual Composition



Lesson materials to bring for 1st session (available at Booklink one week before the start of workshop):

  1.  One A3 size sketchbook
  2.  One A4 size sketchbook
  3.  Pencils: HB, 4B and 6B
  4.  Pen: Pilot V7, Pentel or Uni-Ball Signo Gel Ink Pen UM-170 or equivalent

October 2023

IMPact@SUTD is a regular update featuring works by SUTD Faculty, Researchers, Students and Research Centres/Labs. We hope to create awareness of the Research by SUTD within the SUTD community and beyond. Share with us your SUTD works today so that we can include it in our next update.



[A person wearing glasses and a blue shirt    Description automatically generated]

Data security of machine learning applied in low-carbon smart grid: A formal model for the physics-constrained robustness<http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.apenergy.2023.121405>

Applied Energy





[A person with long black hair wearing glasses    Description automatically generated]

Large portfolio allocation based on high-dimensional regression and Kendall's Tau<http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/03610918.2023.2245176>

Communications in Statistics-Simulation and Computation



[A person in a white shirt    Description automatically generated]

Recent advances in the combination of organic solvent-free extraction, chemical standardization, antioxidant assay, and cell culture metabolomics for functional food and its by-product<https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/10408398.2023.2245040>
Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition



SUTD Author: David Yau



SUTD Author: Yue Mu



SUTD Authors: Leo Chen Huei, Ong Eng Shi



“Success of tools like ChatGPT created a lot of recent interest in generative machine learning (ML). However, prior results in domains like image processing show that manipulating just a few bits in an adversarial setting may mislead the ML into patently wrong answers. These answers raise severe security concerns in emerging cyber-physical systems, e.g., online control of a low-carbon smart grid for agile adaptation to sustainable renewables. The power flows in question are subject to laws of physics, as well as concomitant checks for bad data, whose roles in the ML's cybersecurity are underexplored. In this paper, we adopt a tree ensemble model to provide novel tight lower bounds for the tolerance of physics-constrained ML against adversarial manipulation. The results illustrate impacts on a classical N-1 security problem for power systems.”







“This paper introduces the Kendall's tau unconstrained shrinkage regression for the classical mean-variance (M-VAR) method, or KUSR-MV, as a robust portfolio optimization approach. It enhances asset returns and demonstrates superior high-dimensional portfolio allocation accuracy in empirical studies, maintaining risk constraints while improving the Sharpe ratio.”







“Green extraction technology is a sustainable and eco-friendly method for acquiring bioactive compounds from natural sources. By minimizing harmful solvent use, it mitigates environmental impact and preserves ingredient nutritional value. Our work describes the recent advances in green extraction technologies, chemical standardization, and biological characterization methods for functional food applications.  ”

Restricted

To all SUTD students,

We are recruiting participants for a human-robot interaction study.

This study will take no more than 60 minutes (including a 5-minutes break). Each participant will be reimbursed a $10 Grab voucher for participation. The participant will view hypothetical scenarios of human-robot interaction rendered on storyboards and then answer a short questionnaire for each scenario. This is subsequently followed by a short 25 minutes focus group discussion.

Inclusion criteria:

  1.  SUTD undergraduate students not enrolled in the Principal Investigator's (i.e., Jeffrey Chan/HASS) courses during September term 2023 or January term 2024.
  2.  SUTD community members who are parents.

We have also attached the recruitment poste, in PDF, for you here.

You can simply reply to this email if you are interested in participating.

Thank you.

Jeff

Subject: About MA 1D - second instalment


Restricted

Hi everyone,

Below this message is the first message I sent concerning the 1D project. So the message below is a reminder of what was shared earlier as I believe most of you now are working on the MA 1D project.

Further to what was shared earlier, the plots required in the 1D can be situated on each sheet (e.g. 45 cm 1st etc) with the ax, ay and az data. The ax_bar, ay_bar and az_bar required will come from the "Stationary" values (upright for ax, ay and tilted for az). There is no need to put the plots in the pdf.

Instead, the pdf file will contain your solution to part 4i. Be "warned" that the algebra is not trivial - certainly more than a few lines so work through slowly and carefully. The purpose of the question is to work out (analytically) what is that critical C value that minimizes the error function given. Recall that the C here refers to the drag coefficient and the drag force is the drag coefficient multiplied by the square of the radius and the square of the velocity of the object.

An objective of the MA 1D is to use Excel for the plotting and the regression analysis. So any other method (e.g. Python) will not be accepted.

Note that when you submit on eDimension, you need to submit both pdf and excel file.

Hope this clarifies a little.


Blessings,
Bernie

Subject: about your MA 1D

Restricted

Hi everyone,

It is heartening to see many of you also working on the MA 1D project and I understand that there have been some disquiet and consternation.

So I want to try my best to resolve this as much as possible.

I apologize for my wordy response but I hope to give this overview. All will be made clear during the Design briefing that is happening next Wednesday.

The MA 1D project is related to your 2D which is about dropping an object from a certain height and this object has an attached parachute.

So before you throw the object, you will turn on the sensor. In the course of the object's drop, it will experience some free-fall and the parachute opens, hits the ground and then you will turn off the sensor.

The data you see in the 1D data file contains all of these recordings in this sequence. So, the intention is to familiarize you with what is going on for the actual drop in Week 11.

One must remember that when the object is stationary, it is already registering acceleration values in the x, y and z directions (see the upright stationary sheet). This of course assumes that the sensor has been turned on. Haha!!

We also need to consider the case when the object has been tilted (or rather when the sensor is being tilted) but stationary. This is because when the object is being dropped, it will experience an upright and tilted configuration.

When the object is being thrown, we must not forget that the upright and tilted stationary data is also embedded in the sensor values.

But if we want to capture information pertaining to the drop of the object only (because our goal is to analyze the dynamics of the object being dropped), then we need to "subtract out" the stationary upright and tilted portions.

The idea in part 4b is to ensure that any systematic errors in computing the ax, ay and az are removed. One way this is done is to subtract each entry for ax, ay and az with the average values in tw. As such, the ar in part 4b should be close to g for all time entries because the object is still stationary.

Part 4c seeks to just average this out since there is an ar for each time entry. And we can expect that the ar is close to g since the object is still stationary.

Part 4d then showcases the time evolution of the object from the time it is being released to the time it hits the ground. So you can expect that the "a" value is initially 0 (as expected) because the object hasn't yet been thrown.

So if you follow the instructions in the 1D document, then you will see that the values of "a" in part 4d will initially be zero but it attains the free fall g value (as expected).

This makes sense since the object will experience free fall at some stage in its trajectory. The easiest way to visualize this is to plot the column of values that contains this "a" value (as per the formula in the 1D document). You can see that near the "left end" of the plot (the a hits g - this is the free fall portion).

So the idea behind all this is to help you to calibrate your instrument first (what parts 4a, b and c are about) so that from the sensor data (you obtain for the full drop - from object release to free-fall to parachute deployment to hitting the ground), you can determine the various phases of the drop from the sensor data.

Again, sorry if the explanation is long but I hope it is helpful.🙏🙏🙏


Blessings,
Bernie

Dear All,



Join us for a lecture by Thomas Wortmann, Tenure-Track Professor for Computing in Architecture, Institute of Computational Design and Construction on 6th December at Lecture Theatre 5.



Tenure-Track Professor Thomas Wortmann directs the Chair of Computing in Architecture at the Institute of Computational Design and Construction (ICD) at the University of Stuttgart. He also is a faculty member at the International Max Planck Research School for Intelligent Systems (IMPRS-IS). At the Cluster of Excellence Integrative Computational Design and Construction for Architecture (IntCDC), Thomas coordinates the Artificial Intelligence (AI), Data Integration and Feedback Control for Co-Design group of research projects.

Thomas holds a Master in Architectural Design from University of Kassel, a Master of Science in Design and Computation from MIT, and a PhD in Architecture and Sustainable Design from Singapore University of Technology and Design. Before joining ICD, Thomas taught at National University of Singapore and held a position at Xi’an Jiaotong-Liverpool University in Suzhou, China. He researches the application of AI methods—such as AI reasoning, AI planning, supervised learning, optimization, and multi-variate visualization—in architectural design and construction processes and leads the development of Opossum, a machine learning-based optimization tool that has been downloaded more than 12.000 times.

We're reaching out to you with a surge of energy and excitement because we have an unbelievable opportunity that's mind-blowing! Picture this: in the not-so-distant future, our extraordinary efforts to transform Mars run into a breathtaking twist. A colossal volcanic eruption threatens to undo years of our meticulous work, but hold on, there's a brilliant twist in the tale!


Within the volcanic debris, our brilliant scientists have unearthed invaluable minerals, setting the stage for a heart-pounding competition. It's a thrilling race against time, and it's where two rival companies, the 'SOAR' and 'GED’' alliances, are unleashing cutting-edge robotic fleets to collect these priceless rocks for processing.



This is your chance to shine, to lead the way in moulding the future of Mars, and to flaunt your technical prowess, teamwork spirit, and innovation on a cosmic stage. We cordially invite you to join us on this electrifying journey and be part of a competition that's bound to be nothing less than out-of-this-world.

- Date: 8-11 Jan 2024

- Location: Campus Centre



Why should you be a part of this?

- Push your limits and unravel real-world challenges with your unique and innovative approaches.

- Build relationships and collaborate with like-minded students who share your love for robotics and space exploration.

- Gain invaluable experience that can set you on the path to a stellar career.

- A once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to be part of shaping humanity's future beyond Earth.



We are eagerly seeking dedicated and passionate students who are poised to embrace this awe-inspiring challenge. To register and secure your spot in the competition, please visit our registration page https://forms.office.com/r/dUBfiURnGk



Don't let this opportunity slip through your fingers. Join us in our mission to shape the future of Mars and leave your indelible mark on the world of robotics and space exploration.



If you have any questions or need additional information, don't hesitate to reach out to us at soar@club.sutd.edu.sg<mailto:soar@club.sutd.edu.sg>



Prepare to embark on an adventure that will push your boundaries, ignite your passion, and leave you reaching for the stars. We can hardly contain our excitement to welcome you to Roboclash 2024: Space Race!




With boundless enthusiasm,

SOAR Roboclash 2024 Committee

Hi everyone,

I apologize for being absent today on short notice.

I got up this morning and felt very dizzy. It is very likely due to a lack of sleep. Since Sunday night, I have only been sleeping 2-3 hours a night. Too many things to do and manage. Haha!!

I thought that by sleeping 7 hours last night was sufficient but it clearly was not. Used to be ok when I was younger (could do it for a week no problem) but clearly, I am getting old now. Haha!!

But I am feeling much better now - just need to slow down a little.

Hope all of you are doing ok too. Don't wait till you get dizzy like me and do get enough rest. Most importantly, stay emotionally sound - take it easy and just focus on what you can do, not what you haven't done.

This is the last phase of Term 1 so give it your best but remember to do your part (in the 1D and 2D) and get enough rest. We can fall sick easily when we are under stress and not getting enough sleep.

Thankfully, MA teaching will resume and wrap up in Week 12.....because I know that Weeks 10 and 11 will be very busy for you. So it is a good time for those who have fallen behind to catch up.

The mid-terms will be released next week in your one cohort class session. The solutions will be discussed in class and there will be time to seek help (in person) for your 2D and 1D (if needed).

Take care and hope you had a good class with Eng Ying and DTP briefing today.

Very shortly, I will be administering the make up exam and will load the HW 2 scores of the entire batch by hand.

Miss all of you and looking forward to seeing all of you back in class next Wednesday (1100-1330); there is no class on Monday.

No worries, I will write to all the students about the special single class session in Week 10 this evening too. Details can be found in the module introduction too.



Blessings,
Bernie

Dear All,



Join us for a fireside chat with Prof Dame Lynn Gladden from the University of Cambridge:



[A person with glasses and a blue background    Description automatically generated]



Prof Dame Lynn Gladden is our IAS@NTU Distinguished Fellow and the Shell Professor of Chemical Engineering at the University of Cambridge. She served as the immediate former Executive Chair of the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC). Its diverse portfolio encompasses a wide range of fields, such as digital technologies, clean energy, manufacturing, mathematics, advanced materials and chemistry. EPSRC is one of the research councils under the UK Research and Innovation (UKRI) government agency. Prof Gladden has also been pivotal in establishing UKRI’s first five-year strategy, including transformative technologies programmes which are an integral part of the UK Government’s Science and Technology Framework.



Prof Gladden was conferred the NTU Honorary Doctor of Science in July 2023 for her significant leadership and contributions to scientific research, the development of research and innovation in Singapore, and her contributions to collaborative research with NTU in carbon reduction and sustainability.



[cid:image002.png@01DA067E.AFEFDF70]

Subject:: Fw: Calling for Participants for Motivation Study
Preview:: From: psych lab <psychlab@sutd.edu.sg> Sent: Thursday, November 9, 2023 10:10 AM Subject: Calling for Participants for Motivation Study Dear student, Different musical, language, and motivational
Message Body::
________________________________
From: psych lab <psychlab@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Thursday, November 9, 2023 10:10 AM
Subject: Calling for Participants for Motivation Study


Dear student,



Different musical, language, and motivational factors have been shown to influence performance in tasks such as physical exercise and learning. We are interested in understanding the underlying mechanism of how these factors affect your performance in cognitive tests, and thus you are invited to participate in this research study (Project title: Music, Language, and Motivational factors in Executive Functioning).



We are seeking students who:

  1.  Are Singaporeans or PR
  2.  Are aged between 18 and 45 years
  3.  Are proficient in English
  4.  Have normal or corrected-to-normal vision and hearing
  5.  Are not clinically diagnosed with or have medical history of any mental, neurological, psychiatric or sleep disorder, and/or mental disabilities
  6.  Are not currently consuming psychoactive medication
  7.  Do not have major physical disability, disease, or motor disorder



You will be asked to 1) complete some cognitive tests (no prior experience is required), and 2) answer some questionnaires about yourself and the cognitive tests. Depending on the group/condition you are in, you may also be asked to listen to music before or in between blocks of some tasks. Also depending on the group/condition you are in, you may be given different types of feedback related to your performance in the cognitive tasks(s). You will participate in one to two sessions, lasting about 3 hours in total. You will be compensated for your participation ($10 in voucher per hour). All data collected in the research will be kept strictly confidential. The study has been approved by the SUTD Institutional Review Board.



If you meet our criteria and are interested to participate, please email the Language and Social Cognition Lab: psychlab@sutd.edu.sg<mailto:psychlab@sutd.edu.sg>

with the subject of your email: “Sign Up for MotivationStudy0004* and with your name and contact details. We will get in touch with you as soon as possible.



We look forward to hearing from you soon!



Sincerely,



Language and Social Cognition Lab

Singapore University of Technology & Design

Cc: Massimiliano Colla <max_colla@sutd.edu.sg>; Omar Ortiz <omar_ortiz@sutd.edu.sg>; Wong Wei Pin <weipin_wong@sutd.edu.sg>; Bong Eng Ying <engying_bong@sutd.edu.sg>; Wu Chunfeng <chunfeng_wu@sutd.edu.sg>; Chandrima Chatterjee <chandrima@sutd.edu.sg>; Anariba Franklin Edwin <franklin_anariba@sutd.edu.sg>; Liu Xiaogang <xiaogang_liu@sutd.edu.sg>; Michinao Hashimoto <hashimoto@sutd.edu.sg>; Sumbul Khan <sumbul_khan@sutd.edu.sg>; Ee Kuo Wei Bernard <bernard_ee@sutd.edu.sg>
Subject: MA for Week 10 and 11


Restricted


Hi everyone,



I know that many of you are feeling tired, maybe weary, maybe even demoralized at all the looming deadlines this month. Your feelings are completely understandable as you may feel that it is all too much and still have classes to attend.



This is why for Maths, there is only 1 class next week (return and go through mid-term and help out in the MA component for 2D) and no class in Week 11.



The purpose is two-fold: first to give all of you some breathing space to focus on your projects but also to allow those who are falling behind in Maths to catch up.



For Week 10, the single class session for the various cohorts are as follows: (same information as in the module information on eDimension).

F01: Fri 17 Nov (1430-1700)

F02: Wed 15 Nov (1100-1330)

F03: Wed 15 Nov (1100-1330)

F04: Thu 16 Nov (1230-1500)

F05: Tue 14 Nov (1000-1230)

F06: Tue 14 Nov (0900-1130)

F07: Tue 14 Nov (1530-1800)

F08: Tue 14 Nov (1530-1800)

F09: Tue 14 Nov (1230-1500)

F10: Tue 14 Nov (1400-1630)

F11: Tue 14 Nov (1230-1500)



The Maths mid-term is being marked so please bear with us. When all the grading is done, I will enable the access and you can take a peek. I will send out an e-mail to everyone. The release of the marks on eDimension is to enable you to check to see if the mid-term exam paper is graded correctly and the tally matches with the eDimension scores.



For those that did not do as well as they had hoped for the mid-term, I want to encourage you to not lose hope and to see the exam as a diagnostic for where you stand – not just in terms of Maths but also in terms of how you have been studying and coping since day 1 this term. It is easy to be feel disheartened especially when so much effort was put in.



Often times, it may not be the lack of effort but how that effort is being utilized in combination with how one manages examination anxieties. Fortunately, this is a pass/fail module so your goal is to cross the 50% mark.



For those who either failed the mid-term or didn’t do as well as expected, DO NOT BE DISHEARTENED. Know what has to be put right (whether it is being more careful with working or clarify what was unclear previously; talk to your cohort instructors if needed) and focus on what needs to get done: to get the best marks possible for your 1D and the Maths component for 2D as well as the final exam.



I find it helpful to have a plan as to what has to be done each day. It is tempting to just focus on one thing until it gets done. But I have found that this can sometimes lead to undue anxieties for the remaining tasks because we never know how long we need to spend on a particular task (especially if it is complex). Doing a little bit each day helps me to see “progress” on all fronts and this in itself builds confidence.



I hope that for those who failed the mid-term, you will seek help from your cohort instructors and the PLS on Fridays.



I am happy to see students working hard because it shows that you are committed to making this term a meaningful one where you begin that journey of growth and maturity. What does working hard mean?



As far as I am concerned, it is not necessarily about how many hours you put in. Instead, it is about doing exhibiting that courage and determination to go out of your usual comfort zone and to put what needs to be put right being put right. But again, I hope that you are not Staying Up Till Dawn to get this done. Haha!! If so, then we need to think about how to work a little more smartly. 😃



Seriously, I hope that the more “relaxed” Maths class schedule in Weeks 10 and 11 will give you some time to catch your breath and get a bit more rest. Indeed when I talk to many students across the cohorts, this is indeed the case for the overwhelming majority of you.



We will then come back to the lesson in Week 12 to wrap up Sections 3 and 4 of the final chapter. So the material will be completed by the end of Week 12. This is to allow you enough time to study and revise for your Maths final exam in Week 14.



So keep up the good and hard work, everyone! Proud of you! 😃







Blessings,

Bernie

Hello Residents,

We hope that you had a well-rested recess week and having a fantastic start to Week 9, settling into your classes, and enjoying the company of friends, both old and new. 1. Cultural Connect: Explore Kazakhstan
Discover the rich cultural tapestry of Kazakhstan by the facts kindly provided to us by a hostel resident, Alen. Learn about Kazakh cuisine, traditional musical instruments, and even pick up a few words in the Kazakh language. Dive into the heart of this fascinating culture!

RSVP here: https://forms.office.com/r/4XWyKhbyf4



About the Speaker: Mr Ng was formerly a Director and the Chief Executive Officer of SIA Engineering Company. Prior to his appointment as the Chief Executive Officer on 1 April 2020, he was the Executive Vice President for Human Resources and Operations in Singapore Airlines (SIA) until 31 March 2020.

Mr Ng joined SIA in 1985 where he was appointed to various senior positions in Singapore and overseas. In 2004, he returned to Singapore to take up the position of President & Chief Executive Officer of SATS. He left SATS to rejoin SIA as Executive Vice President for Human Resources and Planning on 1 January 2008. He assumed the position of Executive Vice President Human Resources and Operations on 1 February 2011 and was in charge of the divisions of Cabin Crew, Engineering, Flight Operations, Customer Services and Operations, and Human Resources.

Mr Ng is currently a Director of SMRT Trains Ltd and a member of the Advisory Board of the Engineering Systems and Design Pillar at the Singapore University of Technology and Design.

Preview:: Restricted Restricted From: SUTD Library <library@sutd.edu.sg> Sent: Friday, November 10, 2023 2:28 PM Subject: Weekly Discovery: Honoka 3D-Prints Furniture, Learning To Forget – A Weapon in The
Message Body::

Restricted

From: SUTD Library <library@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Friday, November 10, 2023 2:28 PM
Subject: Weekly Discovery: Honoka 3D-Prints Furniture, Learning To Forget – A Weapon in The Arsenal Against Harmful AI & more 6 Nov – 10 Nov 2023


Restricted


[cid:image007.png@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

Weekly Discovery
We SHARE to inspire and ignite ideas!



6 Nov – 10 Nov 2023



3D PRINTING

Reverse Engineering Jackson Pollock<https://seas.harvard.edu/news/2023/10/reverse-engineering-jackson-pollock>



3D PRINTING

Honoka 3D-Prints Furniture That "Re-Weaves Tatami into Modern Life"<https://www.dezeen.com/2023/11/03/honoka-3d-printed-furniture-tatami/>



3D PRINTING

3D-Printed Metals with Contrasting Properties Made Using New Method Co-Developed by NTU Singapore<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/1006311>



AI

Learning To Forget – A Weapon in The Arsenal Against Harmful AI<https://warwick.ac.uk/newsandevents/pressreleases/?newsItem=8a17841a8b8b07e0018b8f73a7bd12de>

[cid:image008.gif@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

[cid:image009.jpg@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

[NTU Singapore's Dr Gao Shubo (left) and ASTAR's Dr Li Zhi]

[AI in Indonesia: The current state and its opportunities]

“Can a machine be trained to paint like Jackson Pollock? More specifically, can 3D-printing harness the Pollock's distinctive techniques to quickly and accurately print complex shapes?

“I wanted to know, can one replicate Jackson Pollock, and reverse engineer what he did,” said L. Mahadevan, the Lola England de Valpine Professor of Applied Mathematics at the Harvard John A. Paulson School of Engineering and Applied Sciences (SEAS), and Professor of Organismic and Evolutionary Biology, and of Physics in the Faculty of Arts and Sciences (FAS).

Mahadevan and his team combined physics and machine learning to develop a new 3D-printing technique that can quickly create complex physical patterns — including replicating a segment of a Pollock painting — by leveraging the same natural fluid instability that Pollock used in his work.

The research is published in Soft Matter.”

“At Designart Tokyo, Japanese design collective Honoka exhibited furniture and lighting made by 3D printing a material made from discarded Tatami mats.

The exhibition – titled Tatami Refab Project – displayed lampshades, lighting fixtures, tables, stools, basins and plant holders that appeared to glow thanks to the translucency of the material, which was made from grass and resin.

"Honoka has developed a unique material by mixing biodegradable resin with Igusa grass, which is extracted from Japanese discarded Tatami mats," said Honoka.

"Using ExtraBold's large 3D printer, the project proposes furniture that re-weaves Tatami into modern life."

The Igusa grass is cut from the mats and ground up, before being mixed with biodegradable resin.

The resulting pellets were fed through a large-format 3D printer and assembled to create a range of functional homewares and products.”

“Scientists have developed a new method that can make customised 3D-printed metal parts containing different properties – such as having some regions of the metal stronger than others.

The new technique from the researchers – led by Nanyang Technological University, Singapore (NTU Singapore) and University of Cambridge – uses 3D-printing steps. Unlike traditional metal manufacturing processes, it does not require additional raw materials, mechanical treatment or drastic machining processes to achieve a similar effect, such as coating the metal with a different material, thus potentially helping to reduce manufacturing costs.

Besides designing a 3D-printed metal part with different strength levels, the new process should theoretically also allow manufacturers to design a part with other features, such as differing levels of electrical conductivity or corrosion resistance in the same metal.”

“With the AI summit well underway, researchers are keen to raise the very real problem associated with the technology – teaching it how to forget.

Society is now abuzz with modern AI and its exceptional capabilities; we are constantly reminded its potential benefits, across so many areas, permeating practically all facets of our lives – but also its dangers.

In an emerging field of research, scientists are highlighting an important weapon in our arsenal towards mitigating the risks of AI – ‘machine unlearning’. They are helping to figure out new ways of making AI models known as Deep Neural Networks (DNNs) forget data which poses a risk to society.

The problem is re-training AI programmes to ‘forget’ data is a very expensive and an arduous task. Modern DNNs such as those based on ‘Large Language Models’ (like ChatGPT, Bard, etc.) require massive resources to be trained – and take weeks or months to do so. They also require tens of Gigawatt-hours of energy for every training programme, some research estimating as much energy as to power thousands on households for one year.”

Source: Harvard<https://seas.harvard.edu/news/2023/10/reverse-engineering-jackson-pollock> (30 Oct 2023)

Source: Dezeen<https://www.dezeen.com/2023/11/03/honoka-3d-printed-furniture-tatami/> (3 Nov 2023)

Source: Eurekalert!<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/1006311> (30 Oct 2023)

Source: WARWICK<https://warwick.ac.uk/newsandevents/pressreleases/?newsItem=8a17841a8b8b07e0018b8f73a7bd12de> (2 Nov 2023)



ARCHITECTURE

Creating Energy-Efficient Buildings: The Role of Human Interaction and Sensory Technology<https://www.archdaily.com/1008979/creating-energy-efficient-buildings-the-role-of-human-interaction-and-sensory-technology?ad_campaign=normal-tag>



BATTERY

New Designs for Solid-State Electrolytes May Soon Revolutionize the Battery Industry<https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000738/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=24186&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd=>



CONSTRUCTION

Toward Sustainable Construction: Preparing Liquefied Stabilized Soil from Construction Sludge<https://www.shibaura-it.ac.jp/en/headline/detail/20231101_7070_623_1.html>



ENGINEERING

A Robot Performs Heart Surgery with A Strong but Delicate Touch<https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-03353-3>

[cid:image012.jpg@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

[Figure 1. Design Strategy for Trigonal Chloride Solid Electrolytes          The arrangement of metal ions (yttrium in this case) within each layer affects the ionic conductivity. To ensure the unobstructed movement of lithium ions, the number of metal ions occupying available sites within each layer should be less than 0.444. Furthermore, to create a sufficiently wide pathway for lithium ions within each layer, the occupancy of metal ions should be more than 0.167. Therefore, achieving an occupancy of metal ions between 0.167 and 0.444 within each layer results in a conductive layer with high ionic conductivity]

[cid:image014.png@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

[Three green flexible tubes enter a chambet with walls made of red plastic.]

“How do we create buildings that use energy efficiently? Traditionally, efforts to green the built environment have centered on the physical infrastructure, often overlooking the relationships between people and space. The emergence of the technological era has ushered in "Smart Buildings." that employ machine learning and automation. These innovative structures are designed to operate with impressive energy efficiency, however, they are largely disconnected from their occupants. What if buildings could be made smarter and more sustainable by engaging with their occupants?

"Buildings could be a lot smarter if we leverage the brains of the people inside of it", shares Paul Chávez, Associate, User Experience and Technology Design at Arup, a global sustainable development company. Spearheading the project BREO (Building Resource Expression and Optimization), Chávez highlights the untapped potential of engaging occupants in actively conserving energy in buildings. Buildings consume a significant portion of the world's energy and resources, and yet its occupants often remain detached from the consequences of their energy consumption. BREO is a novel approach to tackling this problem, using sensory technology to create a more intuitive and interactive relationship between buildings and their inhabitants.”

“Researchers led by Professor KANG Kisuk of the Center for Nanoparticle Research within the Institute for Basic Science (IBS), have announced a major breakthrough in the field of next-generation solid-state batteries. It is believed that their new findings will enable the creation of batteries based on a novel chloride-based solid electrolyte that exhibits exceptional ionic conductivity…

This research brings to light the often-overlooked role of metal ion distribution in the ionic conductivity of chloride-based solid electrolytes. It is expected that the IBS Center’s research will pave the way for the development of various chloride-based solid electrolytes and further drive the commercialization of solid-state batteries, promising improved affordability and safety in energy storage.

Corresponding author KANG Kisuk states, “This newly discovered chloride-based solid electrolyte is poised to transcend the limitations of conventional sulfide and oxide-based solid electrolytes, bringing us one step closer to the widespread adoption of solid-state batteries.”

This research was published on November 3, 2023, in Science, which is one of the world's most prestigious scientific journals.”

“Scientists from Japan have developed high-flowability liquefied stabilized soil from construction sludge that could revolutionize the sustainability of the construction industry.

Liquefied stabilized soil (LSS) is made with construction waste and used for filling and backfilling long, confined spaces where traditional compaction is difficult. Using LSS helps speed up construction processes while reducing costs, wastage, and environmental impact. Now, researchers from Shibaura Institute of Technology, Japan have developed a superior, high-flowability LSS from construction sludge with better mechanical properties and fluidity than conventional LSS, which could make the construction industry more sustainable.”

“A soft robot can perform intricate surgical procedures inside a beating heart.

The motion of a pulsating heart, coupled with the narrow and delicate nature of blood vessels, makes minimally-invasive cardiac surgery challenging. To address this, Jacob Rogatinsky at Boston University in Massachusetts and his colleagues engineered a millimetre-scale robot that can enter the heart’s chambers, and a stabilizing device that sits at the heart’s entrance, in the large vein called the superior vena cava.

The stabilizer collapses to 8 millimetres in diameter for insertion into the body. Once it is threaded through the superior vena cava, it can expand to 32 millimetres. The robot, made of small balloon-like structures, can brace itself against the stabilizer and guide existing robotic surgical tools into the moving heart. A Nintendo Wii game controller is used to direct the machine.

The team tested the device on a pig’s vena cava, 3D models of the heart’s chambers and a pig’s heart. They hope that future tests on live animals will confirm that the robot performs well and reveal any complications.”

Source: Archdaily<https://www.archdaily.com/1008979/creating-energy-efficient-buildings-the-role-of-human-interaction-and-sensory-technology?ad_campaign=normal-tag> (30 Oct 2023)

Source: IBS<https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000738/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=24186&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd=> (3 Nov 2023)

Source: Nature<https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-03353-3> (2 Nov 2023)



FIBERS

Flexible Thermochromic Fabrics Enabling Dynamic Colored Display<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/969209>



METAVERSE

Can AI Make Architects Better Storytellers?<https://www.archdaily.com/1008735/can-ai-make-architects-better-storytellers?ad_campaign=normal-tag>



SUSTAINABILITY

Two Million European Single-Family Homes Could Abandon the Grid By 2050<https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2542435123004026?via%3Dihub>



VIRTUAL MEETINGS

Virtual Meetings Tire People Because We're Doing Them Wrong<https://www.aalto.fi/en/news/virtual-meetings-tire-people-because-were-doing-them-wrong>

[Flexible thermochromic fabrics enabling dynamic colored display]

[cid:image017.jpg@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

[cid:image018.jpg@01DA13E0.3594FED0]

[Niina Nurmi, photo by Mikko Raskinen.]

“Fibrous devices have attracted more and more research due to their unique one-dimensional morphological advantages such as flexibility, light weight and wearability. In the past decade, a variety of functional fibrous devices have been developed, including conductive, energy harvesting and memory devices, sensors, actuators and lighting devices. Among them, color-changing fibers provide a new direction for the research of new contemporary information display and human-computer interaction due to their extensibility and programmability. When the clothes people wear can change color and pattern instantly with the signal of external environment, it can not only enrich the aesthetics of the clothes itself, but also establish the bridge of natural interaction between users and environment, and realize the timely display and perception of environmental information.

Researchers led by Prof. Guangming Tao at Huazhong University of Science and Technology (HUST), China have been dedicated to research in the field of functional fibers. Prof. Tao’s team has proposed a wet spinning process that can produce a variety of color reversible thermochromic fibers on a large scale, and its excellent mechanical properties and weaveability can be used to produce colorful fabric displays in everyday clothing.”

“This article is the sixth in a series focusing on the Architecture of the Metaverse. ArchDaily has collaborated with John Marx, AIA, the founding design principal and Chief Artistic Officer of Form4 Architecture, to bring you monthly articles that seek to define the Metaverse, convey the potential of this new realm as well as understand its constraints.

Artificial Intelligence is at the genesis of creating fundamental changes in the way we design and construct buildings and cities. Some of these changes will be abrupt and disruptive to normative practice.  Others will take more time to feel the effect of this new technology, but the change will be pervasive.  When combined with the Metaverse, AI will also offer vast opportunities for the profession to expand and grow.  The kinds of spaces and environments we design in the Metaverse will be, in some aspects, very different from what we currently design in the physical world alone. AI evolves every day, and we are compelled to learn while we innovate. AI has proven it is a powerful tool to assist designers and offers the potential to challenge us to alter our design process. Combining AI with narrative design is one of those challenges.”

“Rising energy procurement costs and declining capital costs for renewable technologies are provoking interest in self-sufficiency for individual buildings. In this study, we evaluate the potential of self-sufficient energy supply for 41 million freestanding single-family buildings under current and future (2050) conditions. We identify 4,000 representative buildings, calculate weather-robust cost-minimal energy systems, and transfer the optimization results to the entire European building stock. Our analyses show that buildings in regions with low seasonality and high electricity procurement costs have a high potential for self-sufficiency. Under current techno-economic conditions, 53% of the 41 million buildings are technically able to supply themselves independently from external infrastructures by only using local rooftop solar irradiation, and this proportion could increase to 75% by 2050. By paying a premium of up to 50% compared with grid-dependent systems with electrified heat supplies, building owners could make over two million buildings fully energy self-sufficient by 2050.”

“New research suggests sleepiness during virtual meetings is caused by mental underload and boredom. Earlier studies suggested that fatigue from virtual meetings stems from mental overload, but new research from Aalto University shows that sleepiness during virtual meetings might actually be a result of mental underload and boredom.

‘I expected to find that people get stressed in remote meetings. But the result was the opposite – especially those who were not engaged in their work quickly became drowsy during remote meetings,’ says Assistant Professor Niina Nurmi, who led the study.

The researchers measured heart rate variability during virtual meetings and face-to-face meetings, examining different types of fatigue experiences among 44 knowledge workers across nearly 400 meetings. The team at Aalto collaborated with researchers at the Finnish Institute of Occupational Health, where stress and recovery are studied using heart rate monitors. The paper was published in the Journal of Occupational Health Psychology.”

Source: Eurekalert!<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/969209> (3 Nov 2023)

Subject: MA Updates


Restricted


Hi everyone,



Just to share quick updates with everyone.



  1.  The marks for the mid-term have been officially released. The average (as of 10 Nov) is 28.78/44. I say as of 10 Nov as you have not had the chance to take a peek at the paper so they may be revisions. However, I do not expect that the average to deviate much from this.



  1.  The Homework 1 score is marked out of 21 instead of 20 – as per the original arrangement. Apologies for any confusion this may have caused. This will not make a significant change in your overall scores.



  1.  The solutions to the remaining Practice Questions for Chapter 6 is now available on eDimension as there were requests for early release as a way to help students better manage their schedules. ??



  1.  The solutions to the mid-term will be e-mailed to all of you sometime this Sunday so that you can take a look at it. Next week, in your single class session with your instructors, they will go through the mid-term as well as provide guidance (if needed) on your maths related projects. The important thing is to make sure that your scripts were marked correctly and the sum of the points is correct.



  1.  During the mid-term review, you are allowed to take pictures of your scripts to help you to review and prepare for your final exam. However, they will be collected back at the end of the review because they are needed for quality control purposes.



  1.  The weighted total is given to you as a guide to help you to track your progress towards the 50% mark – which is currently the pass mark for the entire module. So right now, your score should be seen as being out of 36.33% (2 homework, 5.66% each and 1 mid-term, 25%).



  1.  The final exam is out of 25% and will mainly focus on Chapter 5 and 6. However, you are required to know differentiation.



  1.  For the final exam, you will be given a table of integrals. Please see attached for your reference. I will release this again closer to the end of the term so that everyone remembers. However, I thought to release it now so that you can begin to prepare your cheat sheet if you know what is going to be provided in the final exam.



Let me know if you have any further questions. I wish everyone a blessed, restful and hopefully productive weekend ahead.



To our Hindu friends, a blessed Diwali.

Subject: MA midterm exam solutions


Restricted

Hi everyone,

Attached is the solutions to the MA mid-term exam you just sat for.

On the day that the scripts are returned, do check to see where you went wrong and take pictures of your scripts that you will need for your self-study and revision. This is to enable you to make comparisons between your answers and that of the solutions. At the end of the exam review, your scripts will be collected back for quality control purposes.

It is important to ensure that your solutions to the short answer and modelling parts are logical and systematic - regardless of the approach taken. This is important because a common issue experienced in general (for all modules) is that markers don't understand what is being written and the onus is on the student to ensure that what is on your mind is accurately communicated on paper. This is why examinations are a multi-faceted assessment mode - it is not just to reflect what you know but it is also to write down what you know too.

A number of students made careless mistakes in this exam and being a foundational module, it is important that students be able to work through relatively basic problems accurately and not just count on getting part marks for
working done for basic problems.

Speaking to a number of you, I know that some of you might be feeling disappointed with your Maths examination results. This is understandable but I want to encourage all of you to look at the bigger picture here. In good time, you will forget what you got in this exam but I hope that you will be able to retain and further develop your understanding of the concepts taught in this module.

There are a lot of things to be done - such as your 1D and 2D projects. Together for Maths, the 1D and 2D projects make up 30% of your final mark. So do not lose hope but at the same time, don't over-strategize - aim to shoot for how many percent for 1D and 2D. Such efforts (while understandable) are usually futile because a lot depends on your group mates. Thus, the effort must be channeled towards ensuring an accurate (as best as possible) and timely completion and submission of the projects.

There is also the final exam and so I hope that for those who didn't do well in the exam, you will take the opportunity to take stock and see what needs to be rectified to improve in the next two weeks. Though this is a busy period for everyone, I hope that you will use the empty slots for Maths strategically. 😄

If you have concerns about your development in Maths, then do get in touch with your cohort instructors.

Keep up the good and hard work, everyone! 💪💪


Blessings,
Bernie

Of cos SS otherwise why ate you presenting to me?

Instructions for Students:

Please produce a set of PowerPoint slides in response to one of the prompts below. Be

prepared to make a short (15-20 minute) oral presentation during Week 10 in your

recitation sections. All team members are required to contribute to both the visual and

oral presentation. A good presentation will engage with and synthesize ideas found in the

required and supplementary readings in relation to your chosen prompt. Your

presentation should be: 1) Informed in its appropriate selection and accurate

interpretation of readings, methods and key concepts; 2) Insightful in providing an

incisive and novel analysis, appropriately supported by carefully researched evidence and

Phyo Kyawt Khine Tun.

Preview:: From: Entrepreneurship <entrepreneurship@sutd.edu.sg> Sent: Tuesday, November 14, 2023 2:21 PM Subject: [Last call for Registration] ARISE (Venture Building) Demo Day on 17 Nov 2023 ARISE is a
Message Body::
________________________________
From: Entrepreneurship <entrepreneurship@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Tuesday, November 14, 2023 2:21 PM
Subject: [Last call for Registration] ARISE (Venture Building) Demo Day on 17 Nov 2023






[cid:image001.png@01D9FC34.611CDA00]



ARISE is a research commercialization programme that supports researchers to move beyond customer validation to venture creation. Through the programme, research teams learn to develop their business models, business strategies, operations, financial projections and pitching skills with the objective to translate their technology to market.



4 ARISE teams will showcase their technology and commericalise innovation outcomes after eight weeks of hard work.  The teams presenting will include:





[cid:image002.jpg@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

PARIS

An innovative tethered aerial robotics system for solar panel cleaning that employs a proprietary aerial robotics technology with a rub-and-rinse mechanism to ensure safe, efficient, and sustainable cleaning of solar panels to maximize energy output. Prof Foong Shaohui leads the team.



[cid:image003.png@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

Magic3D

An advanced Multi-material 3D printer system that supports a wide range of liquid materials, from soft elastomers to silicone-compatible hard epoxies, enables automated integration of continuous fibres. Unlocking possibilities and widening the scope of 3D printing capabilities. Prof Pablo Valdivia leads the team.







[cid:image004.jpg@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

NeatSens

Specially designed yarns equipped with electronically enabled knitwear that would enable uninterrupted and accurate monitoring of joint load and mobility. The tech enables remote monitoring of patients’ physiotherapy sessions in the comfort of their homes and provides crucial actionable insights for effective physical training outcomes and performance analysis. Prof Low Hong Yee leads the team.





[cid:image005.jpg@01D9FC34.611CDA00]

IM2Cell

Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) is widespread around the world and poses a serious threat to public health. Present Antimicrobial Susceptibility Testing (AST) at hospitals and medical facilities is slow (14-20 hours). IM2Cell’s label-free microfluidic bacterial analysis platform currently can provide quantitative AST results within 30 minutes. Prof Ye Ai leads the team.

Subject: 🚀 Elevate Your Future: Join Our Exclusive Fireside Chat with Former SIAEC CEO Mr Ng Chin Hwee on 22 Nov 2023, 4:30 PM


Restricted


Dear all,



You are invited to join us in the upcoming Fireside Chat with Former SIAEC CEO Mr Ng Chin Hwee.

Date      : 22nd November 2023 (Wednesday)

Time      : 4.30 pm onwards

Venue  : Library Level 2 Parkscape



This is not just an event; it's a unique opportunity to fuel your aspirations and broaden your horizons. Whether you're a passionate aviation enthusiast, a student or a dedicated researcher, this series promises to provide valuable insights that can shape your future career in the industry.



🌟 Event Highlights:

Fire-side Chats with Industry Pioneers: Gain insights from leading experts and professionals in the Aviation industry.

Interactive Dialogue Sessions: Engage in thought-provoking conversations that go beyond the textbooks.

Networking Opportunities: Connect with like-minded peers and establish valuable connections for your future endeavours.



Please register by scanning the QR code in the attached eDM or click the link below.

https://forms.office.com/r/4XWyKhbyf4





About the Speaker:

Mr Ng was formerly a Director and the Chief Executive Officer of SIA Engineering Company. Prior to his appointment as the Chief Executive Officer on 1 April 2020, he was the Executive Vice President for Human Resources and Operations in Singapore Airlines (SIA) until 31 March 2020.

Mr Ng joined SIA in 1985 where he was appointed to various senior positions in Singapore and overseas. In 2004, he returned to Singapore to take up the position of President & Chief Executive Officer of SATS. He left SATS to rejoin SIA as Executive Vice President for Human Resources and Planning on 1 January 2008. He assumed the position of Executive Vice President Human Resources and Operations on 1 February 2011 and was in charge of the divisions of Cabin Crew, Engineering, Flight Operations, Customer Services and Operations, and Human Resources.

Mr Ng is currently a Director of SMRT Trains Ltd and a member of the Advisory Board of the Engineering Systems and Design Pillar at the Singapore University of Technology and Design.



https://www.siaec.com.sg/exec_ng_chin_hwee.html





This event is brought to you by ESD and the Student Interest Group – Aviation.





Best regards,

Robert WIJAYA (Mr)

Manager, Industry Collaborations & Partnerships



Engineering Systems and Design (ESD)

Singapore University of Technology & Design

Message Body::
Restricted




Restricted

________________________________
From: SUTD Library <library@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Friday, November 17, 2023 2:01 PM
Subject: Weekly Discovery: This AI Robot Chemist Could Make Oxygen on Mars, Cultivating Non-Violent Cities: 10 Examples of Friendly Public Spaces & more 13 Nov – 17 Nov 2023


Restricted


[cid:image007.png@01DA195E.930DDB30]

Weekly Discovery
We SHARE to inspire and ignite ideas!



13 Nov – 17 Nov 2023



AERIAL ROBOTS

The Long Jump: Athletic, Insect-Scale Long Jumping Robots Reach Where Others Can't<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/1007913>



AI

This AI Robot Chemist Could Make Oxygen on Mars<https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-03522-4>



AI

New AI Noise-Canceling Headphone Technology Lets Wearers Pick Which Sounds They Hear<https://www.washington.edu/news/2023/11/09/ai-noise-canceling-headphones/>



ARCHITECTURE

Cultivating Non-Violent Cities: 10 Examples of Friendly Public Spaces<https://www.archdaily.com/969940/cultivating-non-violent-cities-10-examples-of-friendly-public-spaces>

[Long jumping robots]

[A view captured by NASA's Curiosity rover of rocks in the Paraitepuy Pass on Mars.]

[A man wearing a surgical mask and headphones walks through the University of Washington campus while holding a smartphone. People walk behind him.]

[cid:image011.jpg@01DA195E.930DDB30]

“A team of engineers from the University of Illinois has published the first known study documenting the long-jumping motion of 3D-printed insect-scale robots.

The new study, published in the journal Smart Materials and Structures, follows a previous publication that documented the same lab’s investigation of vertical jumping in insect-scale robots. The study is led by Professor Sameh Tawfick, an associate professor and Ralph A. Andersen Faculty Scholar in the Department of Mechanical Science and Engineering. His lab, the Kinetic Materials Research Group, studies the development of artificial muscles as part of its focus on bio-inspired materials manufacturing.

“To my knowledge, this is the first time anyone has demonstrated long jumping in insect-scale robots,” Tawfick said of his lab’s accomplishment. “This is significant because it gives the robot planned mobility, where it can now jump from A to B, traversing terrain rougher than its own size.”

“Researchers in China have developed a robot chemist powered by artificial intelligence (AI) that might be able to extract oxygen from water on Mars. The robot uses materials found on the red planet to produce catalysts that break down water, releasing oxygen. The idea could complement existing oxygen-generating technologies or lead to the development of other catalysts able to synthesize useful resources on Mars.

“If you think about the challenge of going to Mars, you have to work with local materials,” says Andy Cooper, a chemist at the University of Liverpool, UK. “So, I can see the logic behind it.”

The study, published in Nature Synthesis, was led by Jun Jiang at the University of Science and Technology of China in Hefei. Jiang and his team used a mobile machine the size of a refrigerator with a robotic arm to analyse five meteorites that had either come from Mars or been collected on Earth but mimicked the Martian surface. The team’s goal was to investigate whether the machine could produce useful catalysts from the material.”

“Most anyone who’s used noise-canceling headphones knows that hearing the right noise at the right time can be vital. Someone might want to erase car horns when working indoors, but not when walking along busy streets. Yet people can’t choose what sounds their headphones cancel.

Now, a team led by researchers at the University of Washington has developed deep-learning algorithms that let users pick which sounds filter through their headphones in real time. The team is calling the system “semantic hearing.” Headphones stream captured audio to a connected smartphone, which cancels all environmental sounds. Either through voice commands or a smartphone app, headphone wearers can select which sounds they want to include from 20 classes, such as sirens, baby cries, speech, vacuum cleaners and bird chirps. Only the selected sounds will be played through the headphones.”

“Violent cities result from social and economic inequality, which also affects the urban landscape and the way we live. In honor of International Cities Day, we have selected a series of projects to reflect on non-violent ways of using public space.

In 2018, Mexican NGO Seguridad, Justicia y Paz (safety, justice and peace) published a list of the 50 most violent cities in the world based on the rate of homicides per 100,000 citizens. Brazil has 17 of the 50 most violent cities, followed by Mexico with 12, Venezuela with 5, and the United States with 4. Meanwhile, the Gini index, a statistical measure to represent the income inequality within a nation or a social group, shows that the four aforementioned countries, as well as the others in the ranking, all have high coefficients, between 41 and 53, meaning they have a high degree of income inequality among their population. It is important to point out that all these countries were colonized and have been victims of genocide and mass slavery throughout history, resulting in a social structure that marginalizes minorities.”

Source: Eurekalert!<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/1007913> (13 Nov 2023)

Source: Nature<https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-03522-4> (13 Nov 2023)

Source: UW<https://www.washington.edu/news/2023/11/09/ai-noise-canceling-headphones/> (9 Nov 2023)

Source: Archdaily<https://www.archdaily.com/969940/cultivating-non-violent-cities-10-examples-of-friendly-public-spaces> (31 Oct 2023)



ENERGY

Energy Transition: A Super-Model to Guide Policy Makers<https://www.unige.ch/medias/en/2023/transition-energetique-un-super-modele-pour-guider-les-politiques>



HEALTHCARE

Artificial Intelligence: Unexpected Results<https://www.uni-bonn.de/en/news/209-2023>



MACHINE LEARNING

Using Deep Learning to Process Raw Photoacoustic Channel Data and Guide Cardiac Interventions<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/1007917>



SEMICONDUCTORS

Thermal Transistors Handle Heat with No Moving Parts<https://spectrum.ieee.org/thermal-transistor>

[cid:image012.jpg@01DA195E.930DDB30]

[Relative proportions of edges in protein-ligand interaction graphs]

[A photoacoustic approach to guiding cardiac catheters involves short laser pulses delivered using an optical fiber attached to a catheter, while a special signal transducer picks up the ensuing ultrasound waves generated within the heart.]

[close up of a computer chip with an orange wavy line coming out the middle]

“How can we ensure that an energy policy will achieve its objectives? To find out, scientists and public authorities can rely on computer models of varying degrees of accuracy. However, these models have a number of limitations, including the fact that they are not very effective for generating projections on a regional scale. A team from the University of Geneva (UNIGE) has designed a super-model to simulate the spread of three green technologies in Swiss municipalities by 2050. It is based on available statistics and combines twelve existing models of technology growth, while testing their relevance. The results, published in the journal PNAS Nexus, could help inform political decision-making.”

“Artificial intelligence (AI) is on the rise. Until now, AI applications generally have “black box” character: How AI arrives at its results remains hidden. Prof. Dr. Jürgen Bajorath, a cheminformatics scientist at the University of Bonn, and his team have developed a method that reveals how certain AI applications work in pharmaceutical research. The results are unexpected: the AI programs largely remembered known data and hardly learned specific chemical interactions when predicting drug potency. The results have now been published in "Nature Machine Intelligence.”

“Cardiovascular diseases rank among the top causes of death across the world, and cardiac interventions are similarly very common. For example, cardiac catheter ablation procedures, which are used to treat arrythmias, number in several tens of thousands per year in the US alone. In these procedures, surgeons insert a thin, flexible tube called a catheter into the femoral vein in the leg and navigate their way up to the heart, where the problematic tissue is destroyed using cold or focused radiation.

Even though cardiac catheter-based procedures are considered minimally invasive, the position of the catheter tip must be carefully monitored and controlled to prevent damage to the heart. In most cases, surgeons rely on fluoroscopy to localize and guide the catheter tip. However, this approach exposes both the patient and the medical staff to ionizing radiation, which can lead to problems such as increased risk of cancer or birth defects.”

“Electronic transistors are central to modern electronics. These devices precisely control the flow of electricity, but in doing so, they generate heat. Now, researchers at the University of California Los Angeles have developed a solid-state thermal transistor—the first device of its kind that can use an electric field to control the flow of heat through electronics. Their study, which was recently published in Science, demonstrates the capabilities of the new technology.

“There has been a strong desire from engineers and scientists to control heat transfer the same way we control electronics, but it has been very challenging,” says study lead author Yongjie Hu, a professor of mechanical and aerospace engineering at UCLA.”

Source: UNIGE<https://www.unige.ch/medias/en/2023/transition-energetique-un-super-modele-pour-guider-les-politiques> (6 Nov 2023)

Source: UNI BONN<https://www.uni-bonn.de/en/news/209-2023> (13 Nov 2023)

Source: Eurekalert!<https://www.eurekalert.org/news-releases/1007917> (13 Nov 2023)

Source: IEEE Spectrum<https://spectrum.ieee.org/thermal-transistor> (13 Nov 2023)



SUSTAINABILITY

Food Waste Prevention in Europe Can Generate Major Footprint Savings<https://food.ku.dk/english/news/2023/politicians-can-prevent-major-food-loss-and-waste-in-the-food-chain-from-farm-to-table-in-europe/>



SUSTAINABLE DESIGN

Dissolvable Binder for EV Batteries Wins 2023 Earthshot Prize<https://www.dezeen.com/2023/11/08/earthshot-prize-winners-2023/>



VIDEO CONFERENCING

"Zoom Fatigue": Exhaustion Caused by Video Conferencing Proven on A Neurophysiological Level for The First Time<https://www.tugraz.at/en/tu-graz/services/news-stories/tu-graz-news/singleview/article/zoom-fatigue-ermuedung-durch-videokonferenzen-erstmals-neurophysiologisch-nachgewiesen>



WARFARE

21st Century Total Wars Will Enlist Technologies in Ways We Don’t Yet Understand, Writes Jordan Richard Schoenherr<https://www.concordia.ca/news/stories/2023/11/08/21st-century-total-wars-will-enlist-technologies-in-ways-we-dont-yet-understand-writes-jordan-richard-schoenherr.html>

[Food Waste]

[cid:image017.jpg@01DA195E.930DDB30]

[A man is sitting in front of a screen attanding a videoconference.]

[Ukraine flag digitized]

“New calculations show that the European countries have great potential for reducing the demand for global food resources and the associated GHG footprint. Researchers have estimated the climate footprint savings that may be obtained from reducing food loss and waste along Europe’s food supply chain by 50 % by 2030…

“Halving Europe’s food loss and waste, together with a redistribution of global food resources, could solve the challenges of food shortages in the world,” says Marianne Thomsen, research leader and professor of sustainable food systems at the Department of Food Science at the University of Copenhagen (UCPH FOOD).”

“Prince William has announced the five projects that are taking home this year's Earthshot Prize, including an AI-powered soil carbon marketplace and a more circular manufacturing process for lithium-ion batteries.

Founded by the British royal in 2021, the annual Earthshot Prize rewards innovative solutions to the world's most pressing environmental challenges – air and water pollution, environmental degradation, waste and climate change.

From more than 1,100 entries, a winner was chosen for each of these five categories and awarded a £1 million cash prize to help scale up the project and increase its positive impact.

"Our winners and all our finalists remind us that, no matter where you are on our planet, the spirit of ingenuity and the ability to inspire change surrounds us all," Prince William said in a speech at the awards ceremony in Singapore.”

“Following the COVID-19 pandemic, the increase in virtual interactions has created a new challenge: fatigue caused by video calls, also known as Zoom fatigue or videoconference fatigue. This exhaustion, characterized by a feeling of tiredness and alienation due to too long or inappropriate video-based communication, had previously only been investigated through surveys and self-assessments by users. An interdisciplinary research team led by René Riedl from the University of Applied Sciences Upper Austria/Campus Steyr and Gernot Müller-Putz from Graz University of Technology has now managed to provide neurophysiological evidence of videoconference fatigue.”

“As new technologies like artificial intelligence, unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) such as drones and so-called ‘cyberweapons’ such as malware and Internet-based disinformation campaigns become integral to our daily lives, researchers are working to grasp the role they will play in warfare.

Jordan Richard Schoenherr, an assistant professor in the Department of Psychology, writes in a new paper that our understanding of warfare is now outdated. The role sociotechnical systems—meaning the way technology relates to human organizational behaviour in a complex, interdependent system—plays in strategic thinking is still far from fully developed. Understanding their potential and their vulnerabilities will be an important task for planners in the years ahead.”

Source: UOC<https://food.ku.dk/english/news/2023/politicians-can-prevent-major-food-loss-and-waste-in-the-food-chain-from-farm-to-table-in-europe/> (6 Nov 2023)

Source: Dezeen<https://www.dezeen.com/2023/11/08/earthshot-prize-winners-2023/> (8 Nov 2023)

Subject: MA HW3 Q3 and Q4 help

Hi everyone,

Just thought I give everyone a little help. These two questions require you to REALLY understand integration. Apologies if I am disturbing you.

Q3: Here is the trick....use the definition of integration and differentiation in a "different" way.

Let's say we have the integral of f(t) = g(t).

Then, dg/dt = f(t). Yes?

Also, we have

integral of f(t) from t=a to t=b is given by g(b) - g(a). Yes? This is the evaluation theorem from the notes.

So recognize that if we now replace a and b by 2 and 2x^2 respectively and if f(t)=sqrt(4+t^2)/(4t), then

G(x) = g(2x^2) - g(2).

So how do we find G'(x)? How do we differentiate g(2x^2). Good revision of midterm material. 😉

Q4: What is the equation of a circle of radius c and what does the integral of that equation mean? How does this link to the area of a portion of a circle?

The purpose of these two questions is to try to get everyone to think along the lines of not just first going after a formula when you see an integral but to pause first and see what the integral is actually "saying" to us.

Hope the above helps.

Keep up the good and hard work, everyone. 💪💪



Blessings
Bernie

Dear all,



You are invited to join us in the upcoming Fireside Chat with Former SIAEC CEO Mr Ng Chin Hwee.

Date      : 22nd November 2023 (Wednesday)

Time      : 4.30 pm onwards

Venue  : Library Level 2 Parkscape



This is not just an event; it's a unique opportunity to fuel your aspirations and broaden your horizons. Whether you're a passionate aviation enthusiast, a student or a dedicated researcher, this series promises to provide valuable insights that can shape your future career in the industry.



🌟 Event Highlights:

Fire-side Chats with Industry Pioneers: Gain insights from leading experts and professionals in the Aviation industry.

Interactive Dialogue Sessions: Engage in thought-provoking conversations that go beyond the textbooks.

Networking Opportunities: Connect with like-minded peers and establish valuable connections for your future endeavours.



Please register by scanning the QR code in the attached eDM or click the link below.

https://forms.office.com/r/4XWyKhbyf4





About the Speaker:

Mr Ng was formerly a Director and the Chief Executive Officer of SIA Engineering Company. Prior to his appointment as the Chief Executive Officer on 1 April 2020, he was the Executive Vice President for Human Resources and Operations in Singapore Airlines (SIA) until 31 March 2020.

Mr Ng joined SIA in 1985 where he was appointed to various senior positions in Singapore and overseas. In 2004, he returned to Singapore to take up the position of President & Chief Executive Officer of SATS. He left SATS to rejoin SIA as Executive Vice President for Human Resources and Planning on 1 January 2008. He assumed the position of Executive Vice President Human Resources and Operations on 1 February 2011 and was in charge of the divisions of Cabin Crew, Engineering, Flight Operations, Customer Services and Operations, and Human Resources.

Mr Ng is currently a Director of SMRT Trains Ltd and a member of the Advisory Board of the Engineering Systems and Design Pillar at the Singapore University of Technology and Design.

Subject:: Fw: Security Advisory: Phishing Email
Preview:: From: IT Service Desk <help-it@sutd.edu.sg> Sent: Monday, November 20, 2023 3:56 PM Subject: Security Advisory: Phishing Email Dear SUTD Community, Background It has been brought to our attention
Message Body::
________________________________
From: IT Service Desk <help-it@sutd.edu.sg>
Sent: Monday, November 20, 2023 3:56 PM
Subject: Security Advisory: Phishing Email


Dear SUTD Community,



[cid:image001.png@01DA1BCA.1B1BEE50]





[1]Background

It has been brought to our attention that are phishing emails using the display subject title “QUICK TASK” sent to the SUTD Community.

[Not from SUTD email address]Some of you may have received an external email address with jmpth101@gmail.com<mailto:jmpth101@gmail.com> or from different senders.

[cid:image007.png@01DA1BCA.1B1BEE50]



[cid:image008.png@01DA1BCA.1B1BEE50][cid:image009.png@01DA1BCA.1B1BEE50][The purchase was made on behalf of the sender, without providing any details in a rushed manner.][The content of the email does sound suspicious.][3][2][cid:image018.png@01DA1BCA.1B1BEE50]



Three points show this email is a phishing email. Please look at the picture above showing why this email is phishing.





Please note that the threat actors may use other public email domains to continue sending the exact nature of phishing emails. It is a typical phishing email and modus operandi used by threat actors. Please continue to stay vigilant and follow the below-recommended mitigation measures.



Recommended Mitigation Measures

  *   Delete the email
  *   Do not respond to any suspicious email with unknown subject headers.
  *   Do not open any unknown attachments or scan any unknown QR code.
  *   Do not click on any unknown links.
  *   Report to the IT Service Desk (help-it@sutd.edu.sg<mailto:help-it@sutd.edu.sg>) when you receive such emails immediately.





Regards,

Office of Cybersecurity

SPRING 2024 UROP PROJECTS ARE OUT, GRAB THEM NOW!



To view the list of available projects and apply, follow the instructions below:



  1.  Login to MyPortal<http://myportal.sutd.edu.sg/> > Go to Navbar (top right corner) > Navigator > Self Service
  2.  Proceed to UROP/UTOP for Student > Apply for UROP/UTOP Programme
